segments.text: Okay, start out with, tell me how you got into the service.
Are you familiar with the Berry Clan?
No, sir.
Okay, this was back in the days where they had universal military draft for physicians.
It was a real pain to get into a residency and get drafted.
And also the military needed a way that they could plan on the number of people in different specialties that would be coming in at a certain time.
So they devised a plan called the Berry Plan, Dr. Frank Berry.
And what it did is you could volunteer to go into X branch of the service at
X time.
And the time you could pick was either immediately after your internship or after so much residency had been, you know, partial residency had been accomplished or after you'd finished.
And I got in the, I got in the very plan because I wanted to finish my training.
and get through with it, get out of Houston, because I didn't lose anything down there.
And so, you know, I'm just kind of an orderly person, just about how the desk looked.
And I wanted to finish my training, go into service, and practice my specialty.
So that's how I got into the military.
What year was that?
I must have gotten a commission in about,
I thought, well, I don't remember exactly because my commission was backdated until the time I entered medical school.
So I was commissioned.
My date of rank was 1957, but I probably got in, I mean, I probably signed up in the very plan in 60 or 61 when I was junior or senior in medical school.
And I finished my training in 67.
So when you volunteered for it, you weren't really aware of what was going on in Vietnam and that you might be sent over there?
No.
Probably not, because they weren't really getting heated up about that, about Vietnam in the real early 60s.
We were over there participating, and we thought it was going to be a major deal.
Excuse me.
Now, to get over to once you were in Vietnam,
skip to a few years later.
First of all, what was the general condition of the military hospitals in Vietnam?
Good shape?
I was in the Air Force.
The Air Force did not have a hospital in Vietnam until I guess 1966, maybe 65, 66.
They put a
a big hospital complex in Cameron Bay.

And they had, the only other medical facilities the Air Force had were dispensaries at the various Air Force bases, which was perfectly adequate, because number one, pilots were the healthiest bunch of guys in the world.
I mean, if you had anything wrong with you, you can't be one.
So they really didn't need a hospital, and the Army had excellent facilities
within two or three miles of each of the Air Force dispensaries.
And the Navy hospital up at Da Nang was just superior.
The facilities were excellent.
So where did, once you got into Vietnam, where did you spend most of your time?
I spent time, I was assigned to the Air Force hospital at Cam Ranh Bay.
And then I had to visit the various dispensaries in the country as a consultant.
and some in the Venture Hospitals.
Okay, so I guess you probably saw other hospitals, though.
Oh, yeah.
Okay, so some of these questions may be fine answering based on those other ones rather than one you ever had.
I don't know.
Like the picture that a lot of Americans get of Army hospitals, many of them who aren't familiar draw that picture from shows like MASH.
And to clear the record, how do they compare it?
The facilities were much superior in Vietnam.
At the hospitals.
I can't say anything about aid stations.
I guess they had gone from MASH units to MUST units, I guess, by Vietnam.
And I can't remember what MUST stands for.
But some people operated in MASH-like facilities.
But by and large, the evacuation was so good,
that people got from the field to a really well-equipped hospital quickly.
And most of the work was really done in well-equipped facilities.
The personalities and attitudes are remarkably similar to the MASH people.
One of the first meetings I ever went to after I got back from Vietnam was in Atlanta.
And I picked up a copy of a book called MASH
at the airport in Dallas.
And I thought they were going to divert the plane and put me off in New Orleans, because I laughed so hard at it.
Because I knew everybody in the book.
You mentioned field hospitals and other hospitals.
But can you clarify a little bit, what was the actual outline of the military hospital system?
Oh, it's been so long, I've probably blown a lot of it.
In the Air Force, the chain of command was from the base dispensary to the hospital at Cameron, so that was no problem.
With the Marines and the Army, there's been a lot of this stretching me.
See, I guess you had battalion aid stations.
which were mainly concerned with picking up and triage of casualties.
And from there, the people were evacuated, I guess, to the field hospitals.
And the Army, the Navy had the NSA hospital.
at Da Nang, which took care of most of the major work that came out of I-Corps.
And then the Army had an excellent hospital in Pleiku that served most of the Central Highlands.
We got some of that fallout at Cameron, in that general area.
And then the Army had a big, big field hospital down in Saigon, obviously, and one at Ambitui.
I don't remember.
Some funny little name down there.
But the evacuation was so good, really, that I think most of the people really got into it.
secure facilities fairly rapidly, and it was a good, a fairly decent atmosphere for the doctor to work in.
Or on the subject, I don't know what you've done about other people to talk to, but Dr. Jack Walker, who's the internist here in town, was at one of the Army hospitals down near Saigon, and he was
I guess Jack would now see you then, so he was at a level where he could probably tell you more about our organization.
I've talked to Dr. Lee.
I've got to set up a time to talk to him, maybe, because I need more information.
Jack was a career officer, and Ed and I were both just passing through, so Jack might really give you some insight that Ed and I can't do.
I know the hospital you're at might not apply to this question, but I was curious as to how much danger the hospitals were in as far as attacks from the VC or under attack.
Mine was in absolutely no danger at all.
Cameron was attacked one time when I was there and it was sort of just a little token effort.
They just threw some mortars in out on the edge.
Cameron was so big and so well protected.
Some of the American military personnel
did work in some provincial hospitals as part of the pacification program and you made rounds with guns there and you operated in your pod because that was not very secure.
I had friends down in the Delta that routinely were shelled when they were operating.
The naval facility up in Da Nang was interesting because it was up on the top of the rise.
And on one side of the rise was the Monkey Mountain airfield, which was a marine airfield.
And on the other side of the rise was a swamp that the VC owned.
And the VC would sit in the swamp and shoot mortars over the hospital in the airfield.
You know, the Navy has flag of regression here and there.
They were up there working like slaves, people shooting at them.
But when it came time to eat, they'd go down and they'd sit down at the table and the Philippine busboys would serve them and they would eat off China.
You know, act like a gentleman for 45 minutes and then go back to the war.
But I was, at Cameron, I was really sort of in the womb.
But it certainly wasn't that way all over.
People in Pleiku got hit several times.
Denying was never secure.
Saigon got pretty crazy at the end.
And then the guys out in the aid stations and all, they were in constant power, I would imagine.
Ever since the Civil War, I've been looking at the different wars through Vietnam.
Each war makes remarkable advancements in sanitation habits, of course.
In a civil war, the majority of the people died because of poor sanitation.
And I know that Vietnam, that it was much, much more improved than that.
But was there still a problem with unsanitary?
Not in any of the areas that I went.
Not in the United States military areas.
Some provincial hospitals, not the little we desired in the 80s, but no, I don't think so.
That's what I expected.
When we went up to 410 there, the Air Force sent you to the field service school or whatever.
They teach you how to wear the uniform, how to sleep, how to be an officer, a gentleman.
And they taught you how to...
build sanitary things for urinals and latrines and what-not.
But to my certain knowledge, I never went in plus bid.
I went in flush toilets, running water, and foam bid.
Was the number of doctors and medics adequate for the amount of casualties you all encountered?
It was, except during the Tet Offensive in 68.
And that was tough.
But most of the time, most of the places that I went, they had doctors standing around.
You don't have any idea about a guess on the patient to doctor ratio?
No, I can't give you a number on that.
Speaking about the personnel, how was the quality of
Many of the people didn't volunteer, but were drafted, I suppose.
They're generally good quality doctors.
Yes.
Yeah.
They're good quality.
I think I saw very little drug abuse.
That one guy that I'm almost certain was smoking pot.
I don't know of any that were taking hard drugs.
Alcohol abuse was pretty prevalent.
But the people that were in position, command, whatever you want to call it, were all fully trained, good people.
Mainly because of the beer plant, because they'd been able to get people who had already completed their training and were well qualified in their specialties.
And the people who had just had
an internship or one year of residency were assigned as general medical officers and they were in dispensaries and seeing colds and gonorrhea and just kind of like the clinic at home.
And so I think the quality of the medicine that was available was excellent.
Was there much difference between the drafted and the people who got in for a career or volunteered?
Well, it's back to the MASH philosophy.
Most of us did not have a great deal of respect for the regular Army medical officers.
Some of them were really excellent people, but most of them were not as well trained as people that were going to be back into the civilian force.
They weren't as well motivated.
Some of them had been, you know, it's hard to be judgmental about them because they'd been stuck at desk jobs and not practicing medicine for years.
My first hospital commander in Vietnam was a guy that, when he got out of medical school, he did an internship in the service.
He became a flight surgeon, where the only thing he saw were healthy young men.
He got a degree in preventive medicine, which is fine, but it doesn't help you practice.
It doesn't help you take care of sick people.
Maybe it helps you keep people from getting sick, but that isn't much good when people are getting shot, because you can't prevent that kind of stuff.
And one of our anesthesiologists told him that.
He said, Jerry, the problem with this hospital is the boss has a degree in preventive medicine.
And the only thing you do is go around here and prevent medicine.
And I think that was the attitude that a lot of us had about the regular army guys.
Some of them I thought were suboptimal.
A large number of them had just been out of touch with clinical medicine for years.
And a few of them were absolutely superb.
Was there adequate medical supplies available in Vietnam?
Yes.
Was the equipment and supplies found there very comparable to what you would find in an American hospital at the time?
I had almost everything I wanted and if I didn't have it I could use it again.
Generally, a patient could survive in a military hospital in Vietnam as easily as they would have been in a hospital.
I think care of the critically wounded patient in the average military hospital in Vietnam was probably better.
than it is in the average civilian hospital in the United States because they're attuned to taking care of critically sick people.
They don't have anybody in there with headaches and constipation.
They've got people that have died.
And the corpsmen and the nurses and the physicians, everybody was attuned to getting on it and taking care of bad problems and not being afraid of anything.
That's a problem a lot of people have taken care of sick people.
They're scared of them.
Oh, he's dying.
He's dying.
You can't hurt him.
You can try to do something for him.
That's sort of the attitude that most of the people had.
The Navy Corpsmen were absolutely superb.
I was, first place, they were up there with the Marines and our Corps really getting shot up bad.
And a lot of them did get shot and then evacuated them down to us for secondary care.
and kept them until they were ready to go back to duty.
I probably kept the Navy corpsmen a little longer than I should have.
Number one, because they didn't want to go back and get shot anymore.
Number two, they sure were good help.
I loved having them around.
With the nature of the war injuries, I read an article on the number of
injuries contributed to gunshot, or whatever.
I know that much blood was needed to replace the lost blood.
Was that ever a problem, finding enough blood?
It never was at Cameron.
I didn't hear it talked about a lot.
I had my secretary looking for a little booklet.
Let me give you the title of it.
called the Second Syncopac, C-I-N-C-P-A-C, Surgical Conference, John Hay Air Base, Philippines, 25-28 March, 1968.
This was a deal the military put together.
Those of us in country didn't know what was happening to people.
You know, patch them up and then they'd go to a casualty staging unit and get on the C-141 and they'd go to the Philippines or Japan to convalesce.
And we didn't know what our results were.
And the guys in the Western Pacific didn't know what we had done because the records we got lost so often and the records were so skimpy.
So they put this conference together
in the Philippines, so those of us in country that were taking care of people initially could get together with the people that were giving them tertiary care.
And I can't find my copy of the thing, but I have Daphne looking for it.
As I recall, it's pretty good and could probably answer some of those questions you have.
If we're not able to find it, we might can get it through the government printing office or Surgeon General's office.
We'll look for it if we want.
Okay, good deal.
I mentioned that I'd seen some statistics, but at your hospital, what were the prevalent injuries due to combat?
Okay.
Uh...
In what location?
What type?
What was the cause of it?
The vast majority of them were fragmentation wounds that made it in.
And the vast majority were by and large soft tissue wounds.
Yeah, I had a big orthopedic service.
I had a big orthopedic service.

I'm being a little vague about that because our hospital we had the 12th USAF hospital and then the 22nd Casualty Staging Flight and physically they were in the same building but on paper they were two separate commands and

I got confused about the evacuees that were coming into the casualty staging flight, which we had to go over and stabilize and be sure things were all right and send them over, and then the ones that were in the hospital itself.
What were the prevalent diseases not related to combat?
Hilarious.
And it got to be a problem because down in the south,

the plasmodium vivax was the real malaria bug and the prophylaxis for it was excellent and if you took your chloroquine and bremoquine you didn't get vivax malaria and if you did get it you got vivax malaria and you got over it but up in the north
They had a different bug, as I recall, it was falciparum malaria.
And it was a bad actor.
It really was a bad actor.
And initially, every time you got malaria, you got shipped out of the country.
And the kids didn't want to be there, found out about that, and they quit taking chloroquine and primicune because all their friends had had
Plasmodium bivax malaria, and they got sick, and they got sent to Japan, and they got well, and they were out of the country, and that was great, so they wouldn't take it.
But then they got an I-Corps, and they got the damn falciferum stuff, and they started dying from it.
And to sort of break that habit up, the Army put a big 6,000-bed malaria hospital, 6,000 beds, a major hospital, down on the sands bed out of Cameroon.
Just so malaria wasn't a ticket out of the country.
Why catch it if you're going to have to stay in Vietnam anyway?
But that was a bad problem.
All my readings I've done so far, most of them have come from the 60s, early 70s.
They seemed to shy away from VD.
I don't know why they do that, but they just don't talk about it much.
But I know it was a major problem.
Very common.
And they had some strains of gonococcus that were imported from Thailand.
Extremely resistant to all the antibiotics we had at the time.
I did not get involved in treating much VD, fortunately.
But the GMOs were pulling their hair out with some of the strains of gonorrhea that were coming through there because they were just resistant to everything we had.
I don't think you could have shot them with that.
Was there any steps taken to prevent what you know about them?
Well, what can you do?
They weren't.
One of the standbys

civilian world, a guy that knows he's going to go someplace where he's going to be exposed, he'll get the old friendly doc to give him some no-sweat pills, you know, some antibiotics to take before he goes.
I don't think that was done.
Mostly it was a matter of trying to educate people, but you've got to...
a bunch of 18, 19-year-old kids that have been over there getting shot at, and send them to Bangkok, and somebody says, GI, you seem to be a movie star.
And she's a good-looking little thing.
It's hard not to get exposed to some of those things, particularly to tell you how wonderful you are and how good-looking you are and what a war hero you are.
It was a bad problem.
Most people who came down with renal disease, did they not see any more combat, or did they usually get treated and then went back to war?
Treated and then back.
And if they had one of the strains, the policy was you could not come home as long as you were infectious, which made people behave on their last R&R usually anyway.
Like the earlier wars...
I don't know if that was really policy or not.
That was certainly what everyone was threatened with.
No, I remember reading something like that, but they couldn't come in.
Certainly should have been.
Infection.
I don't know if that was a problem in the earlier wars.
How big of a problem was it in Vietnam?
Pretty much have it under control.
Yeah, I think so.
I think the...
the experience in treatment of soft tissue injuries in earlier wars, that is, you know, clean them up and leave them open, uh, stood us in awfully good stead.
And then the first real war in the antibiotic area, uh, era, uh, was Vietnam and decent antibiotics, I guess, in Korea.
Now I don't, I don't think, uh,

It certainly wasn't the horror that it was, say, in the Civil War and the First World War and the early wars, because the wounds were... We learned that the other wars had taught us how to handle wounds.
Obviously, there was some, but if you'd leave them open, they'd usually be open.
What drugs, antibiotics, whatever, did y'all use mostly?
Oh, I guess ampicillin was probably...
Big drug there.
Tetracyclines were useful.
Penicillin.
It's amazing.
Penicillin's still the best antibiotic around.
It was the first one we really came up with.
Chloramphenicol.
Chloramycin, whatever you want to call it.
It's sort of... Chloramphenicol got a bad rap for a long time because of the blood disgraces it causes.
It's super antibiotic.
It really kind of salvaged some of its reputation in Vietnam, and I think it's probably being used more now than it was 20 years ago.
What drugs or therapy was used to reduce pain?
What do you mean?
What do you mean?
I'm sure so many
So many guys get used to using trade names.
And Demerol slips off the tongue easily.
And a lot of Demerol is used.
We use morphine primarily.
It's extremely effective.
It's extremely cheap.
Was it readily available?
Was there always being relief available?
Yes.
How much?
of the diseases would you attribute to being in Vietnam?
How much did they get because they were there that they wouldn't have gotten if they had been somewhere else?
Being involved strictly with surgery, I just don't think I can answer that question.
OK. Psychiatric.
people who were admitted for psychiatric reasons, what percentage, just to round about guess, were admitted to the hospital you were at for psychiatric reasons?
Oh, if I were just guessing, I'd say 8% to 12%.
I don't know if we did.
I don't think we did.
Three shrinks.
I don't know.
That's just a hip shot, I don't know.
It seems to me like they just had one ward, and we had, as I recall, 12 wards, so that's where I came in.
I guess more importantly than how many was, did this number change over the time that you were there?
Towards the end of your period there, did you see a lot more people coming in besides captains?
I don't think so.
The only place I would have seen them would be in the casket staging flights.
And those would have been the only ones that were really grossly psychotic, unable to function.
The guys that were just banged up in the head because of what was going on every day were probably still able to get by and were treated locally.
And I really don't know what sort of outpatient load their psychiatrist had.
What was the approximate survival rate of patients that were wounded?
Another guest speaker.
We didn't lose many that made it to the hospital, but I don't know
I don't know how many went straight to the morgue or the helicopter.
Yeah, that's the main thing.
Those that made it to the hospital.
The Bible was excellent that much.
Of those that were admitted to the hospital, was the majority returned to further combat, or were they...
with the majority?
I would imagine the majority went back to work.
I'm almost certain of that.
Again, it's hard to make that judgment because none of them that came through the Casta Station flight were going back.
They were all going to Japan or the Philippines and probably going back to that.
Okay.
You've already said a few things about the evacuation system in Vietnam, and I've read almost everything I've read praises that.
Can you tell me a little bit about the helicopter evacuation system?
I don't know if you worked much with it, but I know that most of your patients came from that.
How did it work?
The guys that flew those things were all crazy.
They'd do anything to get you out of the vehicle.
Very dedicated people.
I don't know what their capacity rate was, but I suspect it was higher than almost anybody else, except maybe the Marine second lieutenant.
They'd get called in, and they'd go.
And they'd bring in as much as they could.
And had the greatest respect in the world for those men.
I lost some very good friends flying those things.
I thought that was to help people get killed, to try to keep up with people dying.
And then the outpatient, or the outpatient, the outcountry evacuation system was excellent.
The planes were all well equipped.
I flew one of them a couple of times, and it was sort of like being in a hospital.
The big C-141.
That C-9A Nightingale, WC-9A was modified as a patient carries a flying ambulance.
It was a superbly designed ambulance.
That was the biggest improvement over earlier wars like Korea.
Can you think of anything else that was an improvement, medical-wise, over, say, Korea?

I think in my field, in chest and vascular surgery, I think my generation of military surgeons owed such a tremendous debt to the guys that were in Korea, because that's where they started learning how to handle vascular wounds.
and the changes in philosophy about how to handle chest wounds was very important for it.
See, all those young guys that would have been Trapper and Hawkeye, by the time Vietnam came around, they were all professors.
Guys like Frank Spencer, just pick almost any guy that's
professor in a major program right now, and the chances are he was either a Hawkeye or a Trapper.
Can you think of any lessons that were learned as a result in medicine in Vietnam that had an effect on the future of medicine today?
I'm not sure we made any great medical discoveries in Vietnam.
If we didn't, it would be surprising because war has almost always been good for surgery.
The surgeons have learned something down there every time they had to go to war.
And I really don't know what we came up with.
Probably
As much as anything, we learned something about resuscitation of the severely injured person, getting blood volumes restored, and the importance of doing that.
How to take care of the body.
that the wound happened to be in.
I don't think we made much improvement in wound care, but I think in general care of the wounded person probably did, as far as fluids and electrolytes.
Learning the importance of acid-base balance, things that are pretty casual.
I don't know.
Is every soldier that joins the Air Force, is he trained in some way in first aid?
Not just medical corps, I mean anybody who joins?
I don't know.
Well, the reason I'm asking is although the helicopter evacuation system saved many, many lives, I know that there's a lot of times that the helicopters couldn't get in there.
an hour or two.
And I've taken a few first aid and EMT classes.
And they talk about the golden hour and stuff.
The first hour after injury is the most important.
And I was wondering why couldn't, I was thinking that maybe every soldier should be trained somehow in first aid just to apply the pressure at the right place or whatever.
I suspect it's illogical to think that they all don't have some kind of basic first aid training.
The heart of that situation, of course, is your corpsman.
You know, in all the military movies, somebody gets shot, the first thing you hear them say is, corpsman!
That's a good way to get in a lot of trouble with good military units.
Because your commanding officer wants you to call that corpsman by his first name.
Because when those other guys hear corpsman, they want to shoot the one that gets out.
If you shoot him, you know,
That makes your effective kill rate better if you can take care of the ones that's trying to hurt you, help you, wound you.
I've known some Marine officers that will use you pretty good if you call for a corpsman.
You better call for Fred, you know, if you ever, because he didn't want anybody, he didn't want anyone.
He didn't want anybody who was called to work.
I just started thinking about that when I read an article that said some people died just because of blood loss where they were thought to have stopped the pressure that could have prevented them.
That's why I brought that up.
Most people with rudimentary first aid training don't do it.
Have you seen me out there?
They put a tourniquet on a venous injury.
How many, of course you weren't at a field hospital, so you might not have seen this, but I was wondering how many hypochondriacs, people who were looking for a way out of the war.
A lot of them.
I can't give you a number, but a lot of them.
How did you deal with these?
I said, I'm sorry, John, you know.
I'm sorry you don't do well.
I mean, I don't know what you're wrong with.
You have to go back to work.
That's easier in surgery.
You'd have to be, you'd see the occasional guy that would picket an incision or something, you know, to get it infected or get it open.

The policy in the Marine Corps is seven days, or at that time the policy in the Marine Corps was seven days after an appendectomy, you go back to the field, full duty, coach your pack, 40-yard march, whatever.
And you see a lot of people that really, you know, they don't get well as quick as they should.
That's motivation, I guess.
Back to when you got, how long were you in Vietnam?
One year.
One year?
And then you came back and you were still on the search when you came back?
I was wondering how it was, life back at home for a doctor returning from Vietnam.
Was it hard to find work?
I was still in the Air Force.
I went up to the Scott Air Force Base in Illinois for a year, which was really superb.
I fought them.
I didn't want to go down the middle of a corn patch, which is what Southern Illinois is.
It was the Air Force Chief Referral Hospital for Pulmonary Disease, and it was like having a year of residency for me.
It was super.
And I don't think anybody had trouble finding a place to go practice after they got out of the service, after Vietnam.
Your work.
We know that some of the Vietnam vets, some people that have provided had a hard time back in society.
I was just wondering if the doctors had the same problem.
No, they didn't see the combat thing around there.
I don't think so.
I imagine...
I imagine there's probably a higher incidence of the drug and alcohol abuse in the Middle East.
I don't have any way to prove that.
I've never seen any statistics on it.
A lot of guys, you know, there were just a lot of guys, and not just medical officers, but everybody.
They were either working or drunk.
Maybe break that pattern.
Speaking of addiction, was there any problem with
the patients getting addicted to the morphine.
I don't know if you saw any of South Vietnam's medical hospital, but did you see any?
How did ours compare with theirs?
I had been there shortly, and they asked me to go to the prevention hospital.
I was not trying, and I went up there.
At that time, TB was on the wane in this country.
I'd been to the big VA hospital in Houston, and they had a lot of TB.
And I must have seen three or four cases of tuberculosis in Cayman, Houston, which is pretty much from the mid-60s.
I went up to the provincial hospital.
They were trying that day, and they had 75 of them or more.
A lot of leprosy, a lot of trachoma.
Did a lot of South Vietnamese come to your hospital, or did they keep their own?
You just have the Americans.
No.
The policy at our place was that people would go out into the villages and have a clinic, do what you could.
We tried to help out in provincial hospitals, and then we had two civilian wards.
I guess that was...
I don't remember what they called that target, but...
I'm not sure that...
I don't think the Army maybe officially sanctioned filling up their bids with spades.
Number one, because they were getting shot at a lot.
And it was a good PR thing for us to do with the camera.
I did a few parts, some congenital stuff.
I had a lot of Vietnamese working that came on the air base.
They came to work in cattle trucks, and they would turn them over from time to time and get a lot of trauma.
So yeah, we sat there, basically.
